7. File Permissions
Permission Structure
-rwxr-xr--
- = file, d = directory
Owner | Group | Others
Permission Values
Read = 4
Write = 2
Execute = 1

Examples
chmod 700 file.txt – owner full access
chmod u=rw,g=rw,o=r file.txt
chmod 627 file.txt → -rw--w-rwx

Green file name = executable
Running Scripts
chmod +x script.sh
./script.sh

8. Ownership & Groups
Change Ownership
sudo chown newuser file.txt
sudo chgrp admin2 file.txt
sudo chown newuser:admin2 file.txt
sudo chown -R newuser:admin2 my_directory

9. Users & Groups Management
Users
sudo useradd newuser
sudo passwd newuser
su - newuser –> switch user
whoami –> confirm current user
exit –> leave user

Groups
cat /etc/group –> list all groups
sudo groupadd devops
sudo groupdel devops
sudo usermod -aG sudo newuser
sudo gpasswd -d newuser devops
Verify:
groups

10. Sudo & Root
sudo – run command with elevated privileges
sudo su – switch to root user
exit – leave root
Logs
sudo tail /var/log/auth.log – view recent sudo activity

11. Shells
Check Current Shell
echo $SHELL
Change Shell
sudo chsh -s $(which zsh) $(whoami)
Shell Config Files
.bashrc
.zshrc
Located in home directory (~/)

12. Environment Variables
Common Variables
PATH
HOME
USER
SHELL
Temporary Variable
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/bin/java
echo $JAVA_HOME

13. Standard Streams & Redirection
Streams
stdin – input (keyboard)
stdout – normal output
stderr – error output
Redirection
> overwrite
>> append
2> redirect stderr
&> redirect stdout + stderr
Examples
ls nonexistent 2> error.txt
ls nonexistent my_directory &> all_output.txt
ls nonexistent &> /dev/null
/dev/null discards output
